This paper is primarily focused on the development of differentially private generative models for deep learning, which falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG). However, the paper also addresses privacy concerns related to sensitive data, which suggests a potential fit for the sub-category of cryptography and security (cs.CR). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of generative models in computer vision applications, which could place it in the sub-category of computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CV). The paper also mentions the use of federated learning, which is a distributed machine learning technique, potentially placing it in the sub-category of data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the paper discusses the use of autoencoders and variational autoencoders, which are common techniques in artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
